"content": "<style>\nh1.thlex-title { font-size: 1.3em; margin: 0 0 0.4em; }\n.thlex-key { color: #888; font-size: 0.85em; font-weight: normal; margin-right: 0.4em; }\nnav.thlex-index { margin: 0.5em 0 0.75em; }\nnav.thlex-index ul { margin: 0; padding-left: 1.2em; }\nnav.thlex-index li { margin: 0.15em 0; font-size: 0.95em; }\n.thlex-section { margin: 0.6em 0; }\nh2.thlex-heading { font-size: 1em; margin: 0.5em 0 0.2em; }\nh3.thlex-subheading { font-size: 0.95em; font-weight: normal; font-style: italic; margin: 0.2em 0; }\n.thlex-language-sets { margin: 0.3em 0 0.3em 1em; }\n.thlex-language-set { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 0.75em; border-left: 3px solid #e0e0e0; }\n.thlex-language { font-size: 0.8em; color: #888; margin-right: 0.4em; }\n.thlex-lemma { font-weight: bold; font-family: serif; }\n.thlex-translit { color: #555; font-style: italic; font-size: 0.9em; margin-left: 0.3em; }\n.thlex-refs { font-size: 0.85em; color: #444; margin-top: 0.15em; }\n.thlex-paragraphs p { margin: 0.35em 0; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.5; }\n.thlex-image { margin: 0.5em 0; display: block; }\n.thlex-image img { max-width: 100%; height: auto; display: block; }\nfigcaption.thlex-caption { font-size: 0.85em; color: #555; font-style: italic; margin-top: 0.2em; }\n.thlex-abbr { border-bottom: 1px dotted #888; cursor: help; }\n.thlex-xref { color: #1a5fb4; }\nspan[data-bnType=\"bibleReference\"] { color: #1a5fb4; }\ntable.thlex-table { border-collapse: collapse; font-size: 0.9em; margin: 0.5em 0; }\ntable.thlex-table td { padding: 0.2em 0.6em; vertical-align: top; border: 1px solid #ddd; }\ntable.thlex-table tr:first-child td { font-weight: bold; background: #f5f5f5; }\nul.thlex-index-list { margin: 0.4em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; font-size: 0.95em; line-height: 1.6; }\nul.thlex-index-list ul { margin: 0.1em 0; padding-left: 1.4em; }\n.thlex-index-key { font-weight: bold; font-style: italic; }\n</style><h1 class=\"thlex-title\" id=\"REALIA:4.5.8\"><span class=\"thlex-key\">4.5.8</span> Turban, headdress</h1><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">References:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-sets\">\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מִגְבָּעָה</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(migba‘ah)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:40\">EXO 28:40</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod29:9\">EXO 29:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:28\">EXO 39:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev8:13\">LEV 8:13</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">מִצְנֶפֶת</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(mitsnefeth)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:4\">EXO 28:4</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:37\">EXO 28:37</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:37\">EXO 28:37</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod28:39\">EXO 28:39</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod29:6\">EXO 29:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod29:6\">EXO 29:6</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:28\">EXO 39:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:31\">EXO 39:31</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev8:9\">LEV 8:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev8:9\">LEV 8:9</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Lev16:4\">LEV 16:4</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">פְּאֵר</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(p’er)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:28\">EXO 39:28</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Ezek44:18\">EZK 44:18</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Hebrew</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">צָנִיף</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(tsanif)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech3:5\">ZEC 3:5</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Zech3:5\">ZEC 3:5</a></div>\n</div>\n<div class=\"thlex-language-set\">\n<span class=\"thlex-language\">Greek</span> <span class=\"thlex-lemma\">κίδαρις</span> <span class=\"thlex-translit\">(kidaris)</span>\n<div class=\"thlex-refs\"><a href=\"https://ref.ly/Jdt4:15\">JDT 4:15</a>, <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Sir45:12\">SIR 45:12</a></div>\n</div>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Description:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>The turban was a headpiece formed by winding a long piece of cloth many times around the top of the head. It may have been wound permanently and put on and taken off like a hat. See the illustration at <a class=\"thlex-xref\" data-bnType=\"lexiconLink\" data-collection=\"\" data-key=\"\" href=\"#\">6.7 Headdress, turban, hat&lt;REALIA:6.7&gt;</a>.</p>\n<hr/>\n</div>\n</div><div class=\"thlex-section\">\n<h2 class=\"thlex-heading\">Translation:</h2>\n<div class=\"thlex-paragraphs\">\n<p>In some languages there may be a very general word for anything worn on the head. If such a term must be used to describe the High Priest’s headdress, it may be necessary to include a footnote explaining that such a headpiece symbolized the authority of the High Priest.</p>\n<p>The Hebrew words <em>migba‘ah</em> and <em>p’er</em> (literally “beauty” or “decoration”) refer to the headgear of the normal priests. In form their headgear was like the headdress worn by the High Priest, although slightly less elaborate. It will usually be possible to use the same word for both.</p>\n<p>In <a href=\"https://ref.ly/Exod39:28\">EXO 39:28</a> the words <em>migba‘ah</em> and <em>p’er</em> are combined to describe the caps of the ordinary priests. Since both words are used elsewhere to describe a single piece of headwear, different approaches have been tried here in translation. Most translations have a single word, such as “caps” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised Standard Version (1952)\">RSV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Good News Translation (1992)\">GNT</abbr>) or “headbands” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New International Version (1984)\">NIV</abbr>, <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Century Version\">NCV</abbr>). Others take the word <em>p’er</em> to be a modifier of <em>migba‘ah</em>, saying “decorated turbans” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New Jewish Publication Society Version\">NJPSV</abbr>), “decorated caps” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"New American Standard Bible\">NASB</abbr>), “beautiful turbans” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"God&#x27;s Word Translation\">GW</abbr>), or “fancy caps” (<abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Contemporary English Version\">CEV</abbr>). <abbr class=\"thlex-abbr\" title=\"Revised English Bible (1989)\">REB</abbr> treats the two words (in reverse order) as two different items, saying “the tall headdresses and their bands.”</p>\n</div>\n</div>",
